<p class="drop-cap">Modern life runs on clock time: hours, minutes, deadlines, schedules. Relentlessly forward-moving. Monday follows Sunday, January follows December, and each day is essentially interchangeable with the last. The liturgical year offers something radically different. In the Eastern Church, time is not a flat line but a <strong>spiral</strong>, each year revisiting the same events of salvation, drawing the faithful deeper with every revolution.</p>

<p>Christmas is not merely a remembrance of something that happened two millennia ago. It is an encounter with the eternal God who enters time <em>now</em>, in this church, at this Liturgy, for these people.</p>

<p>This is what the East means by <em>sacred time</em>. Not a sentimental feeling at the holidays, but a genuine conviction that the Church's calendar opens windows onto eternity. The feasts are not anniversaries. They are presences.</p>

<h2>The Paschal Cycle</h2>

<p>Everything revolves around <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#pascha">Pascha</a>, Easter. The "Feast of Feasts," the center of the entire liturgical year. Unlike Western Christianity, where Christmas has gradually become the dominant cultural celebration, the East has never wavered: Pascha is supreme. The Resurrection of Christ is the event that gives meaning to everything else: creation, incarnation, crucifixion, and the final restoration of all things.</p>

<p>The Paschal cycle is a moveable feast, its date shifting each year according to a complex calculation involving the spring equinox and the Jewish Passover. Around this central event, the entire year organizes itself. The pre-Lenten weeks prepare the faithful for the Great Fast. The forty days of Great Lent lead to Holy Week. Holy Week culminates in the Paschal Vigil, the most glorious service of the year, celebrated in the deep of night, when the priest emerges from the altar carrying light and proclaiming: <strong>"Christ is risen!"</strong></p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. John Chrysostom, Paschal Homily, 4th century">
  Let no one fear death, for the death of our Savior has set us free. He has destroyed death by undergoing death. He plundered Hades when He descended into Hades. Christ is risen, and not one dead remains in the grave!
</Pullquote>

<p>After Pascha comes the Pentecostarion, the fifty days of celebration leading to Pentecost, the descent of the Holy Spirit. During this season, fasting is suspended entirely. The faithful do not kneel. The mood is triumphant, almost giddy. The Church has faced the worst that death can do and has come out the other side singing.</p>

